NEW

The Burris Fullfield II scope is an enhanced model of the Fullfield version. It boasts a more forgiving sharpness and eye clarity for positioning fore and aft, and left and right. Using modern alloys and machining techniques the weight has been reduced by 20%-25% without affecting durability or optical performance.

Most scopes have three or four potential leak paths in the eyepiece/power ring area. The Fullfield II has but two. These leak paths are sealed with special quad seals rather than low-tech O-rings. To change magnification, turn the entire eyepiece, which is now integral to the power ring. A European-style adjustable eyepiece is easy to use and requires no locking mechanism.

Burris has moved the adjustment system rearward to better accommodates mounting situations. Also, the eyepiece is shorter, allowing even more mounting flexibility.

The Fullfield II has also improved long-range marksmanship. The lower part of the crosshair has ballistic lines that compensate for bullet drop from 100 yards to 500 yards for many common hunting cartridges-it's called the Ballistic Plex.

This is one of the more popular scopes; it is extremely versatile and complements the finest rifles.

title: For Trade:  1942 Lee-Enfield, BSA No. 1 mk. III*: Sporterized
postcontent:
Hi, 

I'm selling an interesting Lee-Enfield sporter that I've had for a while. Details below:


- This gun is obviously a factory re-arsenal that was sold out of service in the 60's: the action and barrel have matching numbers, while the bolt, magazine, and rear sights all match each other. Some unit armorer obviously took donor parts from one gun and mated them to the action and barrel of another. This was very common in post-war, but it's unusual that there are only two different sets of serials. Most FTR's had parts pulled from bins. 

- This gun hasn't been irrevocably altered; the only thing modified beyond repair is the front forestock, when they chopped it down. Barrel's still there, sights, even the buttplate. The buttstock has a hole drilled for a sling swivel, easily filled in. 

- Chambered in .303 British. This is a British WW2 rifle, not a 69's or 70's 7.62 Ishapore. 

- At 150 yards, it's just point and click at that range for a bullseye. Whether you're hunting or target shooting, this gun works for you. Feeds and ejects spent casings very well, the extractor claw is perfect and the mag lips are in great shape. 

- This Enfield is perfect for hunting, target shooting, and would make an awesome project gun for someone wanting to get into Milsurp restoration. Enfields are notoriously easy to break down and re-assemble. No rust in this thing all. 

-Comes with WWII-correct oiler, two stripper clips,  cleaning pull-through, and sling. I'll throw in a nosecap and some front bands if you're wanting to restore it.

Willing to drive a reasonable distance from my home in Cleveland to make a deal. Face to face preferred, but I'll ship this to any FFL or C&R for a flat $20 on top of whatever price or agreement we come to. I'll take a decent cash offer, but would rather trade.

Thanks for reading! More pics available upon request.

Gang - I've found an idiot doing multiple attempts at scamming people on armslist - below is a documented "MO" on what I've seen.  Be aware - recommend face to face only, and don't ever send any money unless you have some sort of escrow service setup.  Here's the email I sent this douche:

Please stop wasting people’s time on these scams you no talent ass clown.  You are exactly why Armslist gets a bad rap.  I’m going to post your “MO” on armslist for all to see and be aware of

1.	You post a nice pistol on armslist with a picture and a very aggressive price – typically colt pythons at $1500.
2.	You have your location set to a State, no specific city (i.e. IL or Texas)
3.	Upon contact via armslist, you respond typical from an outlook.com account (example is FT1 FT1 REDACTED) in which you STRIP OUT the armslist link and subsequently disable to the link so it can no longer be found in armslist.
4.	Your email responses are “canned” and repeated often
a.	Initial response:  Yes still available, where are you located?
b.	Upon letting you know a location within the state you mention in the initial post, you say “Oh, I’m in another state – like Pennsylvania or Texas”
c.	Final response – “Am in Pennsylvania, how would you like to proceed? price includes shipping to your FFL,do you have an FFL dealer that you  work with?  price is $1500”
5.	Upon asking for your phone number, you go silent – do you really get people to send you money???

TIPS:
ALWAYS recommend to go through a FFL for the transfer. make cashiers payable to seller and send to FFL doing transfer. Call FFL 1st and make sure on deal.


I hope you get caught and I’ll do my utmost to make that happen if I ever have a chance.  I’ll be posting your method in Armslist as a scam alert.
